  "bib_entries": {
    "44429627": {
      "title": "Repression of transaminase A by tyrosine in Escherichia coli",
      "abstract": "The formation of an aminotransferase active on aromatic amino acids (transaminase A) was repressed about 5-fold by tyrosine in Escherichia coli K12, B and W. Other amino acids did not have significant effects on the formation of this enzyme. Even under maximal repression of the enzyme by tyrosine, the cells were able to utilize this amino acid as the sole source of nitrogen and the activity of this enzyme was not the rate-limiting factor for growth. It is concluded that normally the enzyme functions biosynthetically, but under special conditions it can catalyze a catabolic reaction in the deamination of tyrosine for nitrogen. Another aminotransferase which acted on phenylalanine but not on tyrosine was found in the various strains of E. coli. This enzyme contributed about one-fifth of the total activity on phenylalanine in the crude extract of cells grown on simple glucose medium. Its formation was not found to be repressed by any particular amino acid."
    }
